  This is a binary tree where each internal node corresponds to a substitution
  operation (non-terminal symbol) and each leaf corresponds to an input symbol
  (terminal symbol). The root of the tree is the start symbol.
  The derivation tree shows the structure of the derivation, with each internal
  node representing a substitution and its children representing the terms
  generated by that substitution.
  The root of the tree is the start symbol of the context-free grammar.
  Each internal node is labeled with a non-terminal symbol and its children with
  the terms generated by substituting that non-terminal.
  The leaves are labeled with terminal symbols.
  The derivation tree captures the structure of the derivation path taken by the
  context-free derivation.
  This is defined in terms of the derivation rules of the context-free
  derivation.
  This is a helper structure used in the proof of context-free derivation
  properties. -/
def DerivationTree (G : ContextFreeGrammar α nt) : Type :=
  G ⊢ { val : ℕ → Option (G ⊢ α) | ... }

/-- A context-free derivation represents the process of deriving a word
  from a start symbol using the rules of a context-free grammar.
  A context-free derivation consists of a sequence of derivation steps.
  Each step involves a substitution operation based on a rule from the
  context-free grammar.
  The derivation starts from a start symbol (e.g., `S`) and proceeds by
  repeatedly applying substitution rules until the desired word is obtained.
  The derivation process can be represented as a binary tree, where each
  internal node represents a substitution operation and each leaf represents
  a terminal symbol.
  The root of the tree is the start symbol. Each internal node has two children
  corresponding to the two terms generated by substituting the non-terminal
  symbol at that node.
  The leaves are the terminal symbols that make up the derived word.
  The derivation tree is constructed recursively, with each step adding new nodes
  corresponding to the terms generated by the substitution.
